-- Rebar Falls Amid Concern That Property Curbs May Reduce Demand
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2013-11-11T02:17:26Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-11-11/rebar-falls-amid-concern-that-property-curbs-may-reduce-demand.html
Steel reinforcement-bar futures in
 Shanghai  fell amid concern that the Chinese government is
strengthening measures to rein in the  property market , reducing
demand for the building material.  Rebar for May delivery, the most-active contract on the
Shanghai Futures Exchange, fell as much as 0.8 percent to 3,633
 yuan  ($596) a metric ton, before trading at 3,643 yuan at 10:07
a.m. local time. Futures declined 0.3 percent last week.  China should aim to start a tax on individual property
nationwide in 2015, China Securities Journal reported today,
citing a report from the government China Center for
International Economic Exchanges. Beijing will ban the presale
of new homes over 40,000 yuan per square meter by the end of
this year, the official Xinhua News Agency reported yesterday,
citing a meeting of the city’s commission of housing and urban-rural development with developers.  “Rebar may continue to fluctuate as it is still facing
uncertainties with regard to government policies,” said Zheng
Ge, an analyst at Wanda Futures Co. in Beijing.  Iron ore  for May delivery on the  Dalian Commodity Exchange 
declined 0.2 percent to 937 yuan a ton. The steel-making
material for immediate delivery at Tianjin port tracked by The
Steel Index lost 0.7 percent to $135.90 a dry ton on Nov. 8.  The spot price of  rebar  gained 0.1 percent to 3,559 yuan a
ton on Nov. 8, the highest since Sept. 13, the according to
Beijing Antaike Information Development Co.  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
